thread.title: Johnny Cueto dominates, Royals beat Astros to return to ALCS
thread.title_full: Johnny Cueto dominates, Royals beat Astros to return to ALCS

author: azcentral.com
title: Johnny Cueto dominates, Royals beat Astros to return to ALCS
text:
KANSAS CITY -- Well, look who finally showed up for the party, just before last call, and absolutely stole the show.
Johnny Cueto, who left the Kansas Royals perplexed all summer, reminded everyone why they traded for him in the first place, suffocating the Houston Astros and leading the Royals back to the American League Championship Series on Wednesday with a 7-2 victory.
Finally, after 13 harrowing weeks, the real Cueto showed up.
There he was, strutting on the mound. Shaking his fists wildly into the air. Pumped his chest. Waving his arms to fire up the sell-out crowd of 40,566 at Kauffman Stadium.
USA TODAY
Houston Astros at Kansas City Royals
This is why the Royals got him.
It was for this game.
This moment.
This night.
It’s October, and in the Royals’ biggest game of their season, Cueto put the Royals on his back, just like real aces do this time of year.
Cueto pounded the strike zone with his 94-mph fastball. He confused the Astros with his breaking balls. And, oh, did he ever rely on his defense, with his teammates making one dazzling play after another.
He retired 19 consecutive battered after Luis Valbuena’s two-run homer in the second inning, stormed off the mound, yelling at himself, telling his teammates it would the last run he’d give up the rest of the night.
It turned out to be the last hit he would give up, before letting closer Wade Davis have the final inning.
Oh, Cueto is back.
And so are the Royals.
The Royals, who won the AL pennant a year ago before falling to the San Francisco Giants in the World Series, are back in the ALCS, starting Friday at Kauffman Stadium.
This time, they’ll be facing their old friends, the Toronto Blue Jays, in a rematch of the 1985 ALCS, won by the Royals enrooted to winning the World Series.
It was the year they had Cy Young winner Bret Saberhagen as their ace.
This time, it’s Cueto, their prized acquisition at the trade deadline, who looked like damaged goods the moment he came to Kansas City.
He left the Royals confused and baffled during the season. He went just 4-7 with a 4.76, including an atrocious five-start stretch in which he yielded a 9.57 ERA.
They didn’t know if he was hurt. Tired. Or simply unable to adapt to the American League,
He dramatically changed his delivery. He tried to find ways to increase his velocity, find a better spin on his off-speed pitches. Nothing worked.
He sure resembled nothing like the man they acquired, who at the time, was the best starting pitcher available, before David Price hit the market.
Little did they realize that Cueto’s mind wasn’t right. He was thinking about his future. He’s a free agent, and every time he struggled, he put more and more pressure on himself. He was costing himself millions of dollars every time he took the mound.
He’s not going to lie, said Royals coach Pedro Grifol, translating for Cueto, “at times it’s been very difficult to take that out of his mind. But the fact of the matter is he’s got to focus on pitching here and performing for this club and this organization.’’
And, oh, what a performance it was.
“I remember (Atlanta Braves president) John Schuerholz telling me that if you make a trade,’’ Royals GM Dayton Moore said, “and whether it’s one hit or one pitch that helps you win a playoff game, it’s all worth it.
This night, the trade was all worth it.
You see, the Royals already had the best record in baseball when they traded for him. They had the division all but mathematically clinched. Yet, the Royals wanted more.
If they are going to go to the World Series again, and win their first title since 1985, they were going to need Cueto.
“We left spring training feeling like it was going to be important to us to make a move,’’ Moore said, “particularly in the rotation. You didn’t know who was going to be available, but I thought we were going to have to do something.
“We had two months to go, and a rotation that really had been struggling. The last thing we wanted to do was put ourselves in position to wear out the bullpen, because that had been our strength. We knew Johnny would give us innings, help solidify our rotation, and be a guy that can match up well against the better teams in baseball.’’
That moment was Wednesday night, and the Royals, who are 10-1 in their last 11 elimination games, proved just too tough for those young Astros to handle.
The Astros, who were six outs away from winning the AL Division Series in Game 4, before blowing a four-run lead, will be back.
They have too much talent. Too much confidence. And plenty of poise.
“It’s about belief,’’ Astros manager A.J. Hinch said. “We believe in this team as a group inside that clubhouse before anybody else did. So there’s a great confidence for us.
“We didn’t spend as many days in first place by accident.
“We dint make the playoff by accident.
“We have a great youthful confidence about us.’’
The Astros will be back.
But the Royals are there now.
“Last year our focus was different,” Royals manager Ned Yost said. “We wanted to break a 29-year spell of not making it to the playoffs. And I felt like the wild-card game really wouldn’t mean anything, just making the wild-card game if we didn’t win.
“When we won, I felt like, ‘OK, we accomplished our goal.’ We wanted to get to the playoffs. And we eventually took it all the way to the World Series. But for me, that was kind of like a bonus.
“This year it’s a different story. Our ultimate goal was to win the World Series. And anything short of that is going to be a goal unaccomplished.’’
Four victories down.
Eight to go.
And with a bonafide ace on the mound.
Welcome back, Johnny Cueto.
Follow Nightengale on Twitter: @Bnightengale
